            <Title>Abraham in Egypt-Following Gods Promise</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="40">
            <Title>Initial Call</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="41">
            <Title>In Egypt</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="42">
            <Title>Foundation</Title>
            <Text>Now the LORD said to Abram, “Go from your country and your kindred and your father’s house to the land that I will show you. 2 And I will make of you a great nation, and I will bless you and make your name great, so that you will be a blessing. 3 I will bless those who bless you, and him who dishonors you I will curse, and in you all the families of the earth shall be blessed” (Gen. 12:1-4).
God’s interactions with Abraham begins not only with a command to leave his family and homeland - but also He commands Abraham to go to a land God would show him. It should be noted that God had not provided Abraham with the details of the promised land. Abraham’s journey is very risky because his is merely pointed in the direction he should go, but given no information about his final destination. We read in Hebrews that “he went out, not knowing where he was going” (11:8b). Following God under these circumstances demanded great faith on Abraham’s part for he was dependent upon God for daily guidance, protection and sustenance. 
Furthermore, God’s promise to provide Abraham with a great nation presented a great challenge to his faith because Sarah was barren! Despite years of failing to produce children, Abraham (and Sarah) did not surrender to unbelief. Instead, they set out on a journey that will test their faith in God’s promises to the limit. Consequently, Abraham actions will have a significant impact upon humanity.</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="43">
            <Title>Separation from the Past</Title>
            <Text>It’s most likely that prior to God calling him Abram was an idolater given what we read in Joshua 24:2 - “Thus says the LORD, the God of Israel, ‘Long ago, your fathers lived beyond the Euphrates, Terah, the father of Abraham and of Nahor; and they served other gods.’” God’s call to Abram necessitated that he disavow any allegiance to the gods of his fathers. The call demanded that he separate himself from idolatry.
Separation from one’s past sinful life is generally known as repentance. One key Hebrew word (šûb - “turn”) expresses repentance as turning away from the wrong path, i.e., sinful behavior, and turning back toward God (DiFransico, Lexham Theological Wordbook). The same idea is found in the New Testament with the Greek word metanoeō which means “to change one’s mind”, resulting in an re-orientation of one’s life (Bauer, A Greek-English Lexicon of the New Testament and Other Early Christian Literature, 640). Paul’s recognition of the Thessalonians conversion in 1 Thessalonians 1:9-10 highlights the nature of true repentance - “For they themselves report concerning us the kind of reception we had among you, and how you turned to God from idols to serve the living and true God, and to wait for his Son from heaven, whom he raised from the dead, Jesus who delivers us from the wrath to come.” Just as God commanded Abram to leave his past behind and center his life on God’s promise, Jesus commands his followers leave behind their past way of living to serve him(Mark 1:15; Luke 13:3). 
As we will learn from the life of Abraham, repentance is not just a one-time event in the life of the Christian. Though known as the father of the faithful, Abraham suffered many faith failures. Each one proved to be a learning experience and over the course of his life Abraham’s trust in God grew. As we come to awareness of the sins and vices that hinder and keep us from experiencing the joy of the Christian life, we realize that there exist much room for spiritual growth in our lives. We must resolve, through the power of the Holy Spirit, to eliminate sinful habits and attitudes that prevent us from fully pursuing the life God intends for us to live. On the other hand, we learn to develop and pursue a lifestyle that will bring honor to God. Just as He did with Abraham, God will provide us the grace to grow in our faith!</Text>
        </Document>
