            <Title>Genesis 13 Lesson</Title>
            <Text>Please read Genesis 13 and answer the following questions:
Context
• What has happened so far in the narrative? Have there been any major events, characters or themes?
• What has happened just prior to the section you are reading?

Observation

What do you learn about the main characters in this section? How does the author describe them? How do they describe themselves?
Moses describes the men of Sodom as wicked and great sinners against the Lord
Abram
Displays faith in God through building and worshipping God at altars
Lot
Displays poor decision-making
Canaanites and Perizzites

Is time or place significant in the events that happen in the passage?

Is there a conflict or high point in the passage?

And Lot, who went with Abram, also had flocks and herds and tents, so that the land could not support both of them dwelling together; for their possessions were so great that they could not dwell together, and there was strife between the herdsmen of Abram’s livestock and the herdsmen of Lot’s livestock.
The high point comes with God speaking to Abram to reaffirm His promise in light of his recent decision

Do you think there is a main point or theme in this section of the story?
God honors Abram’s display of faith through the conflict with Lot and his herdsmen. 
in this scene Abraham’s faith in God is so secure that he can extend land to Lot to make peace. In faith and worship, he builds altars to the Lord, and God rewards him with his voice of promise to give him the land. Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001). Genesis: a commentary (p. 220). Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan.


What surprises are there?
Surprised that Abram did not assert his right to God’s promise to give him Canaan

Meaning

Are there any ‘editorial’ comments from the author about the events in the narrative? How do these comments illuminate what is happening?
The editorial comment in 13:10 foreshadows the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah
The editorial comment in 13:13 notes the wickedness of the men of Sodom, which apparently chooses to ignore. These notes highlights Lot’s poor choice. In ch. 14, Lot will be captured as a slave of war.
Does someone in the narrative learn something or grow in some way? How? What does this person learn?
the altars signify Abraham’s return to faith and his proclamation of claiming the land in the name of God. The narrator underscores Abraham’s return to the place of faith and worship by the repetitive phrase “as far as the site where his tent had been earlier, to the site where he had first built an altar” Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001)
What started as a situation of discontent, quarreling, and friction has now turned into one of divine promise and blessing. Hamilton, V. P. (1990). 
How does the passage point forward to what God is going to do in the future? Does it prophesy or anticipate Jesus Christ in some way?
God reaffirms his promise to give Canaan to Abram and to make him a great nation
Included among the offspring of Abram will be Jesus, the incarnate eternal Word.
Abraham, giving up his rights and implicitly risking the Promised Land to the reprobate Moabites and Ammonites (19:37–38; Deut. 23:3–6; Ezra 9:1), by faith inherits forever “all the land” and “an offspring like the dust” (see Gen. 13:15–16). He prefigures Christ, who humbles himself to the cross and then is so highly exalted that every rational being in heaven and earth will bow the knee at his name. Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001). 
How could you sum up the meaning of this passage in your own words?

Application

How does this passage challenge your understanding about who God is and what he is like?
God’s jurisdiction and sovereignty are not confined to his land. His authority does not stop at the border. He judges an Egyptian Pharaoh for his sins, showing the extension of his power into foreign soil. So too the residents of Sodom may be tagged as “sinners against Yahweh.” Hamilton, V. P. (1990). 
Is there some attitude or behaviour you need to change?
Faith in God gives me the freedom to be generous
Faith in God gives me the freedom to put aside selfish ambition
true Christianity renounces consumerism. Instead, Christians are to relinquish their rights in order to enrich others, trusting God’s promises to provide. Abraham, secure in God, can give up his land. When we are secure in Christ, we do not have to grasp greedily for possessions. Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001)
Do nothing from selfish ambition or conceit, but in humility count others more significant than yourselves The Holy Bible: English Standard Version. (2016). (Php 2:3). Wheaton, IL: Crossway Bibles.
Faith in God gives me the freedom to be a peacemaker
Christians are to give up their rights and prosperity to restore relationship between people. Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001).
Only surrendering the heart and will to God creates peace - it is not secured in circumstances, the ideal environment, etc.
The commendation of peacemakers
Mt 5:9 Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God.
Ro 14:19 So then let us pursue what makes for peace and for mutual upbuilding.
The importance of pursuing peace
Ro 12:18 If possible, so far as it depends on you, live peaceably with all.
Heb 12:14 Strive for peace with everyone, and for the holiness without which no one will see the Lord
Sometimes brothers must separate for the sake of peace Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001).


1. Where did the events in this chapter take place (v3)? (Locate this on the map.)

Bethel/Ai
Jordan Valley
Canaan
